---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import MotionWrapper from "../components/MotionWrapper.astro";

/*
  About — a short letter, not a résumé.

  Layout:
    1. Heading
    2. Prose (first-person, load-bearing only — FCA audit each paragraph)
    3. Signoff — a real handwritten signature (see /public/signature-henry-adams.svg)
       at the close of the letter. The intro reveals the given name; the
       signature closes with the same name in the person's own hand.
       Bookends: spoken name up top, ink on paper at the close.

  Editing policy (for future-me):
    - The daily-tools section is intentionally a SENTENCE, not a grid.
      A résumé-grid of logos with hover interactions fails FCA on two
      fronts: (1) hover affordance on non-clickable chips is decoration,
      (2) a grid of tool names frames this page as a CV — the opening
      line literally says "short letter, not a résumé." Prose says the
      same thing without the framing collision, and scales to any
      length by just… writing more sentences.
    - If you ever need to reinstate the grid, there was a `tools` array
      in the git history before 2026-04-19 that drove a <dl> with a
      .skill-cloud hover. The visual pattern still lives in global.css
      as `.skill-tag` + `.skill-cloud` if you need it again.
    - Never write "fluent in X" or "experienced with Y". The list is
      names, not claims. A tool earns a place by being something you
      reach for in a normal working week. That's the whole filter.
*/
---

<Base
  title="About"
  description="hjadmz — Systems Architect and Design Engineer. Research-backed interfaces, built as systems, not templates."
>
  <MotionWrapper>
    <h1 class="page-heading">About</h1>
  </MotionWrapper>

  <MotionWrapper delay={0.1}>
    <div class="prose about-prose">
      <p class="about-intro">
        Hi, I'm Henry Adams. I go by <em class="alias">hjadmz</em> online.
      </p>

      <p>
        I build interfaces where the research is the product. Not decoration
        on top of a template — the structure underneath is the thing. If the
        foundation can't hold weight, no amount of polish saves it.
      </p>

      <p>
        Systems architect and design engineer, focused on human-centered
        computing. I work on tools where correctness compounds: accessibility,
        motion systems, content architecture. Interested in problems where
        the fix has to work for the user who has the hardest time, because
        that user is frequently me.
      </p>

      <p>
        Governing rule is the <a href="/log/fca-protocol">FCA protocol</a> —
        function over convenience over aesthetics. Every visible decision on
        this site (and in my work) is load-bearing under it.
      </p>

      <p>
        Based in the US — Central time.
      </p>
    </div>
  </MotionWrapper>

  <MotionWrapper delay={0.2}>
    <section class="signoff" aria-label="Signed by Henry Adams">
      {/*
        Real handwritten signature — the authentic artifact, not a type-
        font stand-in. Asset lives at /public/signature-henry-adams.svg
        (preferred, inherits currentColor so it flips with light/dark)
        or /public/signature-henry-adams.png (transparent-bg fallback,
        relies on the CSS filter below for dark-mode inversion).

        Why this beats the prior Mrs Saint Delafield render:
        - A computer font imitating handwriting reads as "handwriting-
          shaped" but never as someone's hand. A real scan/trace
          carries the personality no dress-script can fake.
        - Under FCA, the signature's function is identification.
          Authenticity is function; a stand-in is convenience dressed
          up as aesthetic. Load-bearing choice.

        aria-hidden because the section's aria-label already names the
        author; a screen reader announcing "Henry Adams" twice in one
        moment is noise, not signal.
      */}
      <img
        class="signoff-mark"
        src="/signature-henry-adams.svg"
        alt=""
        aria-hidden="true"
        width="400"
        height="160"
        onerror="this.onerror=null; this.src='/signature-henry-adams.png';"
      />
    </section>
  </MotionWrapper>

  <MotionWrapper delay={0.32}>
    <section class="about-stack" aria-labelledby="tools-heading">
      <h2 id="tools-heading" class="section-label">Daily tools</h2>
      <p class="tools-prose">
        Day to day I reach for <strong>TypeScript</strong>, <strong>React</strong>,
        <strong>Astro</strong>, <strong>Tailwind</strong>, and <strong>MDX</strong>
        for the build. <strong>Figma</strong> and <strong>Pixelmator Pro</strong>
        for design, with design tokens as the contract between the two.
        <strong>Zed</strong>, <strong>Warp</strong>, <strong>pnpm</strong>, and
        <strong>Git</strong> at the desk; <strong>Vercel</strong> for ship.
      </p>
    </section>
  </MotionWrapper>
</Base>

<style>
  .about-prose {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }
  /*
    Intro: first line of the letter. Slightly larger than body so the name
    reads as a greeting, not buried in prose. Full color (not muted) so it
    carries the same weight as the signature at the close — bookends.
  */
  .about-intro {
    font-size: var(--text-step-1);
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-5);
  }
  /*
    The alias inside the opening line. Earlier revision set this in
    Mrs Saint Delafield (the signature face) so "hjadmz" read as a
    handwritten pen-name. User feedback 2026-04-19: the cursive didn't
    fit — dress-script glyphs in the middle of a prose sentence read
    as ornament, not identification. Reverted to a quiet italic in the
    prose face, which is the standard typographic convention for a
    handle or stage name inline ("I go by *hjadmz* online"). The
    <em> tag already conveys the emphasis semantically; the CSS below
    just stops browsers from adding anything decorative on top.
  */
  .alias {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-weight: inherit;
  }

  /*
    Signoff — real handwritten signature, ink on paper.
    No decorative dash line before the mark; that always reads as
    fake. A real signature closes a letter by itself. Fluid size via
    clamp() so the mark reads as a confident artifact on every
    viewport from 4K down to iPhone SE.

    The block-level margins give the signature the breathing room a
    closing mark needs; collapsing margins would let the tools-stack
    border crowd the glyph.
  */
  .signoff {
    margin-top: clamp(var(--space-6), 4vw, var(--space-10));
    margin-bottom: clamp(var(--space-10), 8vw, var(--space-16));
  }
  /*
    Image-based signature. Fluid height via clamp() — one typographic
    control point, scales like every other element. Width auto so
    the image's intrinsic aspect ratio is preserved at every size.

    Color handling:
      · SVG source: author exports strokes with fill="currentColor" and
        it follows the page color automatically (navy in light, off-
        white in dark). Nothing for us to invert.
      · PNG fallback: source is expected to be dark strokes on a
        transparent background. Dark mode inverts with CSS filter; the
        `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` block below handles it.
        If the exported source is the opposite polarity (light strokes
        on transparent), flip the filter — it's a single-line change.

    Left margin nudges the optical edge of the signature back to the
    prose column's left edge; hand-drawn signatures have irregular
    side-bearings and the first stroke usually sits inboard of the
    bounding box.
  */
  .signoff-mark {
    display: block;
    height: clamp(3rem, 7vw, 5.5rem);
    width: auto;
    max-width: 100%;
    margin-left: -0.25rem;
    /* Match the bottom baseline adjustment the type version needed;
       PNG/SVG signatures often sit with leading whitespace at the
       top of the bounding box. Em-based so the nudge scales with
       the clamp() range. */
    transform: translate3d(0, 0.04em, 0);
    transform-origin: left bottom;
    /* Rendering stabilization for the animation path. When
       MotionWrapper fades the block in, sub-pixel rasterization of
       the PNG/SVG strokes can flicker on WebKit. Promoting the
       image to its own compositor layer isolates the opacity
       transition from the image decode pass. */
    will-change: opacity, transform;
    /* If the exported PNG is dark strokes on transparent, no filter
       is needed in light mode — it paints directly. */
  }
  @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
    /*
      Dark mode: invert the signature so dark strokes on transparent
      become light strokes on transparent. This only applies to the
      PNG fallback; an SVG that already uses currentColor ignores the
      filter (it has no intrinsic color to invert). The 1 value is a
      full invert; 0.92 would soften the conversion if the strokes
      ever read as "too hot" against the dark background.

      Note: if the user saves the signature as light strokes on
      transparent (e.g. from a white-ink scan), swap this to the
      light-mode block — one rule, not two.
    */
    .signoff-mark {
      filter: invert(1);
    }
  }
  @media (prefers-contrast: more) {
    /* prefers-contrast: the signature stays at full opacity; the
       browser's own contrast tuning handles the rest. No filter
       change here so the signature doesn't get "enhanced" into a
       different shape. */
    .signoff-mark {
      opacity: 1;
    }
  }
  @media (forced-colors: active) {
    /* Forced-colors: the image's colors are replaced by the system
       palette. Filters are ignored per spec; rely on the system. */
    .signoff-mark {
      filter: none;
    }
  }

  /* ─── Daily tools ─────────────────────────────────── */
  .about-stack {
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
    padding-top: var(--space-8);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);
  }
  /*
    Prose, not a grid. A sentence beats a chip cloud for honesty, and
    <strong> is the single emphasis — the tool names pick themselves
    out of the sentence visually without any hover machinery. Scales
    to any length: add a tool, add a word. The prose column inherits
    the 65ch reading width from .prose conventions.
  */
  .tools-prose {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.65;
    max-width: var(--max-width-prose);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .tools-prose strong {
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text);
  }
</style>
